[[[break]]]added at line 29: *lime {code 

Response to Jeff/ General response to paper

The logical limit on how far to step back when considering causes of disease is which level of analysis will be the most powerful (and feasible when translated into action) when trying to eradicate disease.  It is important to remember that arguing about which causes are relevant is only important because of the consequences of this knowledge.  

The medical model/biological perspective describes disease as purely biological, and emphasises the individual.  Therefore treatment involves the individual being given drugs/ and the administration of other medical technologies.  Sociologists argue that this obscures the fact that disease is distributed unevenly throughout society.  From the sociological level of analysis, disease is caused by belonging to certain socio-economic groups, being of a certain gender, etc (in other words inequality).  From this perspective, manipulation of social structure and processes changes the prevalence of disease.  Anyone who has completed "Sociology of Health and Illness" with Kevin White will be familiar with this sociological argument.  White argues for "the transformation of social structures as the solution to the social, political and economic causes of patterns of disease." (http://www.contemporarynurse.com/13.1/13-1p5.htm).  
 
So why does the medical model remain entrenched?  One of the reasons is that subscription to the medical model of disease allows the status quo to be maintained, we don't have to question inequality or take responsibility for it.  Eg.  Diabetes is much higher in the Aboriginal population.  Why?  Because of poor nutrition etc.   Why?  Because of their low socio-economic status.  Why? Because of inequality in Australia.  It is much easier to stop at a micro level of analysis, rather than addressing society's broader problems.  
 
Link to Kevin White's book "The Sociology of Health and Illness":  http://books.google.com.au/books?hl=en&id=5bHxQBNWGHMC&dq=sociology+of+health+and+illness+kevin+white&printsec=frontcover&source=web&ots=ERgDqGQ9zv&sig=hQuRD_mNbsUIkDXq0A_xIykA_vU#PPP1,M1

 
- Pam Pilkington.
}*
